From a20c2d9df90a2ed8a6a66f061d4aa4f630ad7290 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Tomaz Zaman <tomaz@mono.si>
Date: Sat, 25 Apr 2026 17:55:41 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] sdk_fman/sdk_dpaa/qbman: skip KASAN instrumentation
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The vendored NXP DPAA/FMAN/QBMan trees do plain memset()/memcpy() on
iomem destinations (devm_ioremap'd MURAM SRAM and QBMan portal regions).
With CONFIG_KASAN_GENERIC=y the compiler rewrites these calls to the
instrumented variants, which perform a shadow-byte lookup on the
destination address. iomem regions have no KASAN shadow mapped, so the
lookup itself faults — boot panics during FM_PCD_Init -> AllocFEObjs:

    memset((uint8_t *)p_FeObj->h_FE, 0, FM_PCD_FE_MAX_SIZE);
    ^ p_FeObj->h_FE is iomem (FM_MURAM_AllocMem -> devm_ioremap),
      __asan_memset's shadow check faults on it.

The proper fix is to audit every memset/memcpy against MURAM and
register-block addresses across these trees and convert them to
memset_io/memcpy_toio/memcpy_fromio. That's ~80-200 call sites of
mostly mechanical edits, but the audit surface is the entire vendored
codebase — out of scope for the security-hardening pass.

Instead, scope KASAN to the code we own: cdx, fci, auto_bridge, plus
the rest of the kernel keep full instrumentation; the three vendored
trees are skipped. KASAN_SANITIZE := n only suppresses compiler
instrumentation — KASAN remains globally enabled, so callers that pass
kmalloc'd buffers down into FMAN/DPAA/QBMan still get OOB-write
detection on the calling-context object (KASAN tracks allocations, not
call sites). The only blind spot is FMAN-internal kmalloc'd buffers,
which we already weren't instrumenting (KASAN was entirely off).

Per Documentation/dev-tools/kasan.rst, KASAN_SANITIZE := n is
per-Makefile and does not propagate to subdirectories — every
sub-Makefile that produces objects needs the marker independently.
Touching all 16 Makefiles under sdk_fman (13), sdk_dpaa (1),
drivers/soc/fsl/qbman (1), and drivers/staging/fsl_qbman (1).

Signed-off-by: Tomaz Zaman <tomaz@mono.si>
